        </div>
        <div id="collapseThree" class="panel-collapse collapse" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="headingThree">
            <div class="panel-body">
                <p>
                    The same screener as the Piotroski F-Score Screener, but averaged over several years.
                </p>
                <h2>
                    <a style="text-decoration: none" asp-controller="Screener" asp-action="Screen" asp-route-criteria="@ScreenerConstants.AvgPiotroski">
                        Go to Screener <i class="fa fa-arrow-right"></i>
                    </a>
                </h2>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="panel panel-default">
        <div class="panel-heading" role="tab" id="headingFour">
            <h2 class="panel-title">
                <a class="collapsed" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion" href="#collapseFour" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseFour">
                    EV/Ebitda Screener
                </a>
            </h2>
        </div>
        <div id="collapseFour" class="panel-collapse collapse" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="headingFour">
            <div class="panel-body">
                <p>
                    Also known as the Enterprise Multiple, the EV/Ebitda is a ratio comparing the Enterprise Value(EV) of a company to its earning capicity, as measured by the Ebitda (earnings before interest, tax, depreciation and amortization).
                </p>
                <p>The EV is the value that a private investor would have to pay to acquire the company : not only the equity has to be bought, but the liabilities as well. The cash can be substracted from the total.</p>
                <p>A low EV/Ebitda value means that the company is cheap, because the private investor would have to pay a relatively low price to get the earnings of the company.</p>
                <p>This screener ranks stocks by their EV/Ebitda value, from lowest to highest.</p>
                <h2>
                    <a style="text-decoration: none" asp-controller="Screener" asp-action="Screen" asp-route-criteria="@ScreenerConstants.EnterpriseMultiple">
                        Go to Screener <i class="fa fa-arrow-right"></i>
                    </a>
                </h2>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="panel panel-default">
        <div class="panel-heading" role="tab" id="headingFive">
            <h2 class="panel-title">
                <a class="collapsed" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion" href="#collapseFive" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseFive">
                    Returns On Assets (ROA) Screener
                </a>
            </h2>
        </div>
        <div id="collapseFive" class="panel-collapse collapse" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="headingFive">
            <div class="panel-body">
                <p>Returns On Assets, aka ROA, is simply the ratio of the Net Income of a company divided by its Total Assets.</p>
                <p>It is a simple tool that measures how well a company is using its assets to generate an income.</p>
                <p>Companies with a consistent ROA superior to 10% year after year are often a sign of a very good business.</p>
                <p>This screener ranks companies according to their ROA, from highest to lowest.</p>
                <h2>
                    <a style="text-decoration: none" asp-controller="Screener" asp-action="Screen" asp-route-criteria="@ScreenerConstants.Roa">
                        Go to Screener <i class="fa fa-arrow-right"></i>
                    </a>
                </h2>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
